@page "/WTDcpr"

<div class="first-aid-guide-page">
    <header class="headerwtdfa">
        <a asp-action="Index" href="/WTDfirstaid" class="back-button">
            <i class="fas fa-arrow-left"></i>
        </a>
    </header>

    <main class="content">
        <h2 class="section-title">Basic CPR Guideline</h2>

        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="../imgs/wtd_banners/wtdfa_banners/wtd_cpr.jpg" alt="Person practicing CPR on a dummy" class="cpr-image" />
        </div>

        <p class="intro-text">
            The Philippine Red Cross (PRC) provides CPR training that follows standard 
            <strong>30 chest compressions to 2 rescue breaths</strong> guidelines for adults. 
            The process involves checking the scene and the person for safety, calling for help 
            (emergency services or asking a bystander to call), opening the airway, checking 
            for breathing, and then starting the 30 compressions followed by 2 rescue breaths 
            in a cycle until professional help arrives or the person recovers.
        </p>

        <section class="before-start">
            <h3 class="subsection-title">Before You Start</h3>
            <ol class="step-list">
                <li class="step-item">
                    <span class="step-number">1.</span>
                    <span class="step-content"><strong>Check the Scene:</strong> Ensure the area is safe for you and the victim.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="step-item">
                    <span class="step-number">2.</span>
                    <span class="step-content"><strong>Check the Person:</strong> Tap the person and shout, "Are you okay?" to check for responsiveness.</span>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </section>

        <section class="if-unresponsive">
            <h3 class="subsection-title">If the Person is Unresponsive</h3>
            <ol class="step-list">
                <li class="step-item">
                    <span class="step-number">1.</span>
                    <span class="step-content"><strong>Call for Help:</strong> Call your local emergency number (like 911) or instruct a bystander to call for help.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="step-item">
                    <span class="step-number">2.</span>
                    <span class="step-content"><strong>Open the Airway:</strong> Tilt the head back and lift the chin to open the airway.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="step-item">
                    <span class="step-number">3.</span>
                    <span class="step-content"><strong>Check for Breathing:</strong> Look for chest rise and fall, listen for breath sounds, and feel for air for no more than 10 seconds.</span>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </section>

        <section class="begin-cpr">
            <h3 class="subsection-title">Begin CPR (If No Breathing or Only Gasps)</h3>
            <ol class="step-list">
                <li class="step-item">
                    <span class="step-number">1.</span>
                    <span class="step-content">
                        <strong>Chest Compressions:</strong>
                        <ul class="bullet-list">
                            <li class="bullet-item">Place the heel of one hand on the center of the person's chest.</li>
                            <li class="bullet-item">Place your other hand on top, interlocking your fingers.</li>
                            <li class="bullet-item">Press down hard and fast, compressing about one-third the depth of the chest, or about 2 inches.</li>
                            <li class="bullet-item">Perform compressions at a rate of 100 to 120 per minute.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </span>
                </li>
                <li class="step-item">
                    <span class="step-number">2.</span>
                    <span class="step-content">
                        <strong>Rescue Breaths:</strong>
                        <ul class="bullet-list">
                            <li class="bullet-item">After 30 compressions, give two rescue breaths.</li>
                            <li class="bullet-item">Tilt the head, lift the chin, and deliver a breath, making sure the chest rises.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </span>
                </li>
                <li class="step-item">
                    <span class="step-number">3.</span>
                    <span class="step-content"><strong>Continue:</strong> Repeat the cycle of 30 chest compressions and 2 rescue breaths without interruption.</span>
                </li>
                <li class="step-item">
                    <span class="step-number">4.</span>
                    <span class="step-content"><strong>Continue until:</strong> Professional help arrives and takes over, the person starts to breathe normally, or you are unable to continue.</span>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </section>

        <section class="important-note">
            <h3 class="subsection-title">Important Note</h3>
            <p>
                The PRC offers training courses in Standard First Aid and Basic Life Support (BLS)/CPR 
                with Automated External Defibrillator (AED) to provide a full range of lifesaving skills 
                for various emergencies.
            </p>
        </section>

    </main>
</div>
